An intimate park at the heart of Le Marais district. Its a good place to rest while shopping around. It also has play area for children.

The Marais is one of the oldest districts of the capital. Witness to the remains of our past and the history of France, he has seen its population change and evolve over the centuries. From the Royal Court of Louis XIV to the gay community, through the Ashkenazi Jewish population, "Old Paris" still has a young and dynamic soul that still seduces visitors. Composed of the 3rd and 4th arrondissements of Paris, there are the most beautiful monuments of the capital, a number of which are classified as historical monuments or UNESCO World Heritage.

Square Tranquil

This small square with few trees has several play areas for children, for which it is mainly intended. The square pays tribute to the director of the National Archives, Charles Victor Langlois (1913-1928). The fountain, known as the Guillemites, leans against a wall of the Notre-Dame des Blancs-Manteaux church. This 18th century fountain was moved at the initiative of the Old Paris Commission in 1930. The square, dedicated to fun activities, is very popular with local residents.
